{{Use American English|date=June 2018}}
[[File:Elena Vaelbe by Ivan Isaev from Russian Ski Magazine (crop).jpg|right|thumb|[[Yelena Välbe]] won five medals in Albertville.|alt=A woman wearing a dress standing talking into a microphone]]
{{1992 Winter Olympics}}
The [[1992 Winter Olympics]], officially known by the [[International Olympic Committee]] as the ''XVI Olympic Winter Games'', were a [[multi-sport event]] held in [[Albertville]], France, from February 8 through February 23, 1992. A total of 1,801 athletes representing 64 [[National Olympic Committee]]s (NOCs) participated at the Games in 57 events across 12 disciplines.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Olympic Winter Games Factsheet|url=http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reference_documents_Factsheets/The_Olympic_Winter_Games.pdf|publisher=International Olympic Committee|access-date=August 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810090755/http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reference_documents_Factsheets/The_Olympic_Winter_Games.pdf|archive-date=August 10, 2012|df=|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref>{{IOC medals|games=1992 Winter}} Retrieved June 13, 2018</ref>

Two disciplines were contested for medals for the first time after being [[demonstration sports]] [[1988 Winter Olympics|four years prior]] in Calgary: [[Freestyle skiing at the 1992 Winter Olympics|freestyle skiing]] and [[Short track speed skating at the 1992 Winter Olympics|short track speed skating]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/02/08/how-to-watch-freestyle-skiing-at-the-2018-winter-olympics-in-pyeongchang/|title=Facts about freestyle skiing at the Winter Olympics 2018|last=Root|first=Tik|date=February 8, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503173258/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2018/02/08/how-to-watch-freestyle-skiing-at-the-2018-winter-olympics-in-pyeongchang/?utm_term=.e89f7c392ba7|archive-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freestylecanada.ski/en/events/olympics/top-30-moments/|title=Freestyle Skiing Celebrates 30 years of Olympic History in 2018|publisher=Freestyle Canada|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503173258/http://www.freestylecanada.ski/en/events/olympics/top-30-moments/|archive-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedskating.ca/about/speed-skating-the-sport/short-track-history|title=Short Track History|publisher=[[Speed Skating Canada]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228011515/http://www.speedskating.ca/about/speed-skating-the-sport/short-track-history|archive-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>  In addition, the first women's events were held in [[Biathlon at the 1992 Winter Olympics|biathlon]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/12/sports/albertville-restsova-wins-the-first-women-s-biathlon.html|title=Albertville; Restsova Wins the First Women's Biathlon|date=February 12, 1992|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=B10|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116062228/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/12/sports/albertville-restsova-wins-the-first-women-s-biathlon.html|archive-date=January 16, 2018}}</ref> and a pursuit event was added in [[Cross-country skiing at the 1992 Winter Olympics|cross-country skiing]] for both men and women.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/media-information-report-n1303-.htm|title=Cross-Country Skiing – Media Information Report|publisher=Pyeongchang 2018 Olympic Winter Games|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207161246/https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/media-information-report-n1303-.htm|archive-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>

Following the late-1991 [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], six of the newly independent countries participated together as the [[Unified Team at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Unified Team]], the only Winter Olympics at which they would do so.<ref name="SI">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/19/sports/olympics-unified-team-faces-splintered-future.html|title=Olympics; Unified Team Faces Splintered Future|date=July 19, 1992|work=The New York Times|page=B1|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714214620/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/19/sports/olympics-unified-team-faces-splintered-future.html|archive-date=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1992/01/27/125849/on-to-albertville|title=On to Albertville|last=Johnson|first=William|date=January 27, 1992|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503173258/https://www.si.com/vault/1992/01/27/125849/on-to-albertville|archive-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>  The three [[Baltic states]] of [[Estonia at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Estonia]], [[Latvia at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Latvia]], and [[Lithuania at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Lithuania]] chose to compete independently from the Unified Team.<ref name="SI" />  The republics of [[Croatia at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Croatia]] and [[Slovenia at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Slovenia]] made their Olympic debuts, being newly independent from [[Yugoslavia at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Yugoslavia]].<ref name="SI" />  Following [[German reunification]], the combined [[Federal Republic of Germany]] was represented by one combined team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/23/sports/albertville-germany-gets-a-boost-from-east.html|title=Albertville; Germany Gets a Boost From East|date=February 23, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116045450/http://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/23/sports/albertville-germany-gets-a-boost-from-east.html|archive-date=January 16, 2018}}</ref>

[[Germany at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Germany]] was the most successful team at these Olympics, winning 10 gold medals out of 26 total; both were the most of any nation.<ref name="1992SR" />  The Unified Team came in second in both tallies, with 9 golds and 23 total medals – [[Norway at the 1992 Winter Olympics|Norway]] tied the Unified Team with 9 golds, but had only 20 total medals.<ref name="1992SR">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1992/|title=1992 Albertville Winter Games|publisher=[[Sports Reference|Olympics at Sports-Reference.com]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704141744/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1992/|archive-date=July 4, 2010}}</ref>  [[New Zealand at the 1992 Winter Olympics|New Zealand]]'s [[Annelise Coberger]] won the country's first Winter Olympics medal, the first by someone representing a [[Southern Hemisphere]] nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzhalloffame.co.nz/New-Zealand-Sports-Hall-of-Fame-Inductees/C/Annelise-Coberger|title=Annelise Coberger|publisher=[[New Zealand Sports Hall of Fame]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503173259/https://www.nzhalloffame.co.nz/New-Zealand-Sports-Hall-of-Fame-Inductees/C/Annelise-Coberger|archive-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>  [[Lyubov Yegorova (cross-country skier)|Lyubov Yegorova]] was the most successful athlete, with five medals: three golds and two silvers.  Her teammate on the Unified Team and fellow cross-country skier [[Yelena Välbe]] also won five medals; she had one gold and four bronze medals.<ref name="1992SR" />  Thirty-eight athletes won more than one medal in Albertville, and twenty NOCs won at least one medal.<ref name="1992SR" />

